# Self-signed TLS by default — zero config, works on ANY box including a private IP with
# no public domain. Caddy's `tls internal` uses its own OFFLINE local CA (no internet call,
# no ACME) to mint the cert, which fits the zero-egress story: TLS with no network dependency.
#
# HTTP/3 (QUIC-over-UDP) is disabled: containers commonly can't raise the UDP receive buffer
# Caddy wants (see the "failed to sufficiently increase receive buffer size" warning), which
# left h3 half-broken and caused h1/h2 clients (curl, most SDKs) to get a TLS "internal_error"
# alert during ALPN negotiation. A JSON API has no need for QUIC — h1+h2 is simpler and works.
{
	servers {
		protocols h1 h2
	}
}

# A HOSTLESS address (":8443") makes Caddy treat cert issuance as ON-DEMAND-per-SNI, which
# it refuses by default without an explicit `on_demand_tls` permission policy (a safety
# guard against unbounded cert issuance) — every handshake then fails with a TLS
# "internal_error" alert before your request is even seen. Naming the host(s) explicitly
# makes Caddy issue the cert eagerly at startup instead. Add any other hostname/IP you use
# to reach this box as extra comma-separated addresses below.
localhost:8443 {
	tls internal
	reverse_proxy corrector:5244
}
